        GCEHealthCheck exCreateHealthcheck(java.lang.String name,
                                 java.lang.String host,
                                 java.lang.String path,
                                 int port,
                                 int interval,
                                 int timeout,
                                 int unhealthy_threshold,
                                 int healthy_threshold)
        Create an Http Health Check.
        Parameters:
        name - Name of health check (:type name: ``str``)
        host - Hostname of health check requst. Defaults to empty and public IP is used instead. (:type host: ``str``)
        path - The request path for the check. Defaults to /. (:type path: ``str``)
        port - The TCP port number for the check. Defaults to 80. (:type port: ``int``)
        interval - How often (in seconds) to check. Defaults to 5. (:type interval: ``int``)
        timeout - How long to wait before failing. Defaults to 5. (:type timeout: ``int``)
        unhealthy_threshold - How many failures before marking unhealthy. Defaults to 2. (:type unhealthy_threshold: ``int``)
        healthy_threshold - How many successes before marking as healthy. Defaults to 2. (:type healthy_threshold: ``int``)
        Returns:
        Health Check object (:rtype: :class:`GCEHealthCheck`)

      • exCreateFirewall

        GCEFirewall exCreateFirewall(java.lang.String name,
                           java.util.List<java.util.Map<java.lang.String,Arg>> allowed,
                           java.lang.String network,
                           java.util.List<java.lang.String> source_ranges,
                           java.util.List<java.lang.String> source_tags)
        Create a firewall on a network. Firewall rules should be supplied in the "allowed" field. This is a list of dictionaries formated like so ("ports" is optional):: [{"IPProtocol": "", "ports": ""}] For example, to allow tcp on port 8080 and udp on all ports, 'allowed' would be:: [{"IPProtocol": "tcp", "ports": ["8080"]}, {"IPProtocol": "udp"}] See `Firewall Reference `_ for more information.
        Parameters:
        name - Name of the firewall to be created (:type name: ``str``)
        allowed - List of dictionaries with rules (:type allowed: ``list`` of ``dict``)
        network - The network that the firewall applies to. (:type network: ``str`` or :class:`GCENetwork`)
        source_ranges - A list of IP ranges in CIDR format that the firewall should apply to. Defaults to ['0.0.0.0/0'] (:type source_ranges: ``list`` of ``str``)
        source_tags - A list of instance tags which the rules apply (:type source_tags: ``list`` of ``str``)
        Returns:
        Firewall object (:rtype: :class:`GCEFirewall`)

      • exCreateFirewall

        GCEFirewall exCreateFirewall(java.lang.String name,
                           java.util.List<java.util.Map<java.lang.String,Arg>> allowed)
        Create a firewall on a network. Firewall rules should be supplied in the "allowed" field. This is a list of dictionaries formated like so ("ports" is optional):: [{"IPProtocol": "", "ports": ""}] For example, to allow tcp on port 8080 and udp on all ports, 'allowed' would be:: [{"IPProtocol": "tcp", "ports": ["8080"]}, {"IPProtocol": "udp"}] See `Firewall Reference `_ for more information.
        Parameters:

      • exCreateMultipleNodes

        java.util.List<Node> exCreateMultipleNodes(java.lang.String base_name,
                                         java.lang.String size,
                                         java.lang.String image,
                                         int number,
                                         java.lang.String location,
                                         java.lang.String ex_network,
                                         java.util.List<java.lang.String> ex_tags,
                                         java.util.Map<java.lang.String,Arg> ex_metadata,
                                         boolean ignore_errors,
                                         boolean use_existing_disk,
                                         int poll_interval,
                                         java.lang.String external_ip,
                                         int timeout)
        Create multiple nodes and return a list of Node objects. Nodes will be named with the base name and a number. For example, if the base name is 'libcloud' and you create 3 nodes, they will be named:: libcloud-000 libcloud-001 libcloud-002 :class:`GCEZone` or ``None``
        Parameters:
        base_name - The base name of the nodes to create. (:type base_name: ``str``)
        size - The machine type to use. (:type size: ``str`` or :class:`GCENodeSize`)
        image - The image to use to create the nodes. (:type image: ``str`` or :class:`NodeImage`)
        number - The number of nodes to create. (:type number: ``int``)
        location - The location (zone) to create the nodes in. (:type location: ``str`` or :class:`NodeLocation` or :class:`GCEZone` or ``None``)
        ex_network - The network to associate with the nodes. (:type ex_network: ``str`` or :class:`GCENetwork`)
        ex_tags - A list of tags to assiciate with the nodes. (:type ex_tags: ``list`` of ``str`` or ``None``)
        ex_metadata - Metadata dictionary for instances. (:type ex_metadata: ``dict`` or ``None``)
        ignore_errors - If True, don't raise Exceptions if one or more nodes fails. (:type ignore_errors: ``bool``)
        use_existing_disk - If True and if an existing disk with the same name/location is found, use that disk instead of creating a new one. (:type use_existing_disk: ``bool``)
        poll_interval - Number of seconds between status checks. (:type poll_interval: ``int``)
        external_ip - The external IP address to use. If 'ephemeral' (default), a new non-static address will be used. If 'None', then no external address will be used. (Static addresses are not supported for multiple node creation.) (:type external_ip: ``str`` or None)
        timeout - The number of seconds to wait for all nodes to be created before timing out. (:type timeout: ``int``)
        Returns:
        A list of Node objects for the new nodes. (:rtype: ``list`` of :class:`Node`)
